{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f635217e-3b40-4dd6-8c26-d5ff4f22042a","content":"Here are **3 performance anti-patterns** found in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Recursive wildcard glob (EvalHeavy.csproj, line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` forces MSBuild to walk the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. This is one of the most expensive evaluation operations, scaling with repo size. Prefer explicit file extensions (e.g., `**\\*.txt`) or narrower directories.\n\n### 2. File I/O via property function (EvalHeavy.csproj, line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` during evaluation performs **synchronous disk I/O** in the evaluation hot path. This blocks the evaluation pipeline, can't be cached by MSBuild's evaluator, and re-executes on every evaluation. Move file reading to a target that runs at build time instead.\n\n### 3. Deeply chained imports (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import requires MSBuild to resolve, open, parse, and evaluate another XML file. This chain is 3 levels deep. While manageable here, this pattern scales poorly — consider flattening the hierarchy where possible.\n\n---\n\n**Highest impact fix:** Replace the `**\\*.*` glob with a scoped pattern. **Second priority:** Move the `ReadAllText` call into a build target so it runs only during build, not evaluation.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7605920f-255b-45d2-aad7-6c5a91b631e3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project.\n\nIssues I can identify:\n\n1. **Recursive wildcard glob (`**\\*.*`)** on line 9 of EvalHeavy.csproj — `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" ...>` uses a deep recursive glob that scans the entire directory tree during evaluation. This is expensive, especially in large repos.\n\n2. **Property function doing file I/O during evaluation** — line 13: `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` reads a file during project evaluation. File I/O during evaluation blocks the evaluation pipeline and can't be cached efficiently.\n\n\n3. **Deeply chained imports** — the props files are imported across multiple levels, creating a chain where each one must be resolved and parsed sequentially during evaluation. This cascading dependency adds unnecessary overhead to the evaluation process.","outputTokens":656,"requestId":"1C34:1F45CF:773AECC:83B9C80:69F400E3"},"id":"3e62d1d4-4c75-4070-827d-e6947024a83b","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:25:06.074Z","parentId":"841bcee5-83bf-4805-bfef-506446a8a3bc"}
